@Steve L

I dunno, I could see a pattern emerging and it helped with the crosses, even though at first I wasn't sure there wouldn't be more V's!

Cute theme! Isn't National Ice Cream day coming up? Did I miss it?

@Steve L

Same here, even though as I was solving it, I thought, "I should pause a minute to figure out those shaded squares."

I'm glad I didn't, though. Melted ice cream is so messy.

@Mike
I put off filling that in, but of course one is eventually forced to do The Wrong Thing.  
(If one has trained her horse well, SPURs are not a necessity.  "Cow ponies" are amazing.)

@Diane Schaefer
At such a young age, I’m not sure what’s more impressive: having the taste to recognize perfection, the wisdom to know not to mess with it, or the impulse control not to inhale it!

We didn’t have Carvel where I grew up in California (at least not that I remember), but we did have a local spot called Fenton’s, which the world would later recognize from the Pixar movie Up.

@Diane Schaefer

Apparently the criticism was warranted for Grumpy. Why do you, and people in general, often, insist on all people agreeing on things, and completely trivial ones, too, like liking a puzzle? I've known people who don't love ice cream. And even those who do don't have to love a puzzle with an ice cream theme, do they?

You may disagree with somebody's opinion, but refusing to understand they may have one seems disrespectful.

@Andrzej

I agree that opinions should be respected, but calling someone’s creation “lame” and “useless” while insisting there’s no connection between revealer and theme even though others saw it clearly— is that really an opinion? Or is that just disrespectful denial?

As for ice cream, it’s ok not to like it. That just leaves more for me.

@Steve

And I thank you for your thoughtful posts. We see the world differently, which is as it should be 🙂

Respect!

@Steve

I’m usually on the side of civility on these arguments, and I agree we should be careful about how personal we get. Plus the word “lame” seems like one we should avoid in general. But in this case, I reread Grumpy’s post and it wasn’t that terrible. He didn’t even call the entire puzzle lame, just the theme, and didn’t really attack the constructor personally. Replace the word lame with “lacking” or “disappointing” and I would see nothing particularly objectionable. 

If I were to word this more constructively myself, I would agree that the theme was particularly unnecessary to the solve, and I was disappointed there was nothing in the first revealer to point to ice cream at all. I don’t mind either in the service of a really clever theme but this was a little vanilla. The grid was easy but heck this is a Tuesday. So I wasn’t even going to make a comment today but if I were that would have been it, and I suspect Grumpy and I are not as far apart in our opinions as we are in our language.

@Andrzej

Never never stop posting. You and I don’t always agree but you are always cogent and thought provoking.
By the way not sure if you saw my late post the other day but appreciated your Civ 7 review, I enjoyed it but I see what you mean about the modern age. Not as much fun as building settlements and exploring.

